// Reduce function

const prices = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50];
const total = prices.reduce((acc, price) => acc + price, 0);
console.log("Total price:", total);



const colors = ["red", "green", "blue", "red", "red", "green", "purple"];
const colorCount = colors.reduce((acc, color) => {
    acc[color] = (acc[color] || 0) + 1;
    return acc;
}, {});
console.log("Color count:", colorCount);





--------------------------------------------DAY - 4---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------


Promises


A Promise is used to handle asynchronous operations in JavaScript.
It represents a value that may be available now, later, or never.

function getData() {
    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
        setTimeout(() => {
            resolve("Data received");
        }, 2000);
    });
}

resolve() → called when the operation is successful
reject() → called when the operation fails

setTimeout() ->
Used to execute a function once after a specified delay.

setTimeout(() => {
    console.log("Hello");
}, 2000);
Runs only one time
Delay is in milliseconds (2000 ms = 2 seconds)

setInterval() ->
Used to execute a function repeatedly at fixed time intervals.

setInterval(() => {
    console.log("Data checking again and again");
}, 5000);
Runs continuously
Executes every 5 seconds (5000 ms)



// Asynchronous Programming

Promise Creation: 
- new Promise((resolve, reject) =>{})
    
2. Async:
- TimerFunction (setTimeOut()) is used to delay execution.

3. Resolving the Promise
- resolve("Data received")
- it moves promise to fulfilled state.

4. then():
- handles successful result

5. catch():
- handles errors (rejected state).

6. promise:
new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
// async task
})
resolve - success
reject - error

7. Promise States
Pending - initial state
Fulfilled - resolved successfully
Rejected - error occurred

8. then(): promise.then(result => {
    console.log(result);
    })
- handles success result

9. catch(): promise.catch((error)=>{
    console.log(error);
    })
- handles error

10. setTimeOut(): Used to delay execution

11. fetch("https://api.example.com/data")
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(data => console.log(data))
    .catch(error => console.log(error));